<DOC><DOCNO> AP890301-0261 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0157EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-01 0781</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0813</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Economic growth crawled at a 2 percent annualrate in the final three months of 1988, the slowest in two years,reflecting a worsening trade deficit and lingering effects of thesummer drought, the government said.   The Commerce Department report released Tuesday said the slowdownin the gross national product, the total output of goods andservices, was accompanied by a pickup in the inflation rate. Privateeconomists said they were disturbed by the new GNP statistics.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of existing homes fell 7.4 percent inJanuary, the biggest decline in two years, reflecting a return tonormal buying patterns following a December sales spurt, a realestate trade group reported.   The National Association of Realtors said Tuesday existingsingle-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rateof 3.63 million units in January following a 5.7 percent rise inDecember to a rate of 3.92 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has scrapped itsPremier brand ``smokeless'' cigarette after five months of markettesting, concluding that consumers didn't like the product's smellor taste.   The company's move announced Tuesday followed widespreadcriticism of the cigarette by major health organizations. It alsomarked the first significant product shift since the parent RJRNabisco Inc. was acquired by a private investment firm earlier thisyear for a record $24.53 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. wants banksand savings and loan associations to get its approval before seekingso-called brokered deposits, blamed as a major cause of the Sandamp;Lcrisis.   Regulations will be proposed soon requiring institutions seekingto expand their loan portfolios through the use of the high-interestdeposits to notify the FDIC in advance, the regulatory body'schairman William Seidman told the Senate Banking Committee onTuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A task force of aviation industry andgovernment safety experts has proposed an $800 million overhaul ofthe nation's older Boeing 747s, 737s and 727s to avert safetyproblems.   The group, set up by the Air Transport Association, whichrepresents major U.S. airlines, asked the Federal AviationAdministration to issue a massive ``airworthiness directive'' in aproposal released Tuesday. The directive would require modificationsrecommended in Boeing Co. service bulletins.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. trade deficit worsened in the finalthree months of the year, climbing to $32 billion, reflecting recordhigh levels of both exports and imports, the government said.   The Commerce Department report released Tuesday said the deficitfrom October through December swelled by 10 percent from athird-quarter deficit of $29.17 billion. Economists expressed fearthat the deficit's recent improvement has stalled and will restraineconomic growth this year.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   AFL-CIO officials say their members will picket,boycott and otherwise rally against Eastern Airlines nationwide ifthe company's Machinists union strike.   The pledge by the labor federation Tuesday marked the strongestdisplay of support yet for the machinists at the troubled airline,who have vowed to strike this weekend if no agreement is reached ona contract dispute. In Washington, meanwhile, mediation effortscontinued to avert a walkout.</TEXT><DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Managers at Sears stores nationwide workedto retag items with discounted prices as part of a drastic imagechange for the nation's largest retailer.   By reopening time at noon Wednesday, workers nationwide were tohave rolled back prices on an estimated 1.5 billion pieces ofmerchandise in more than 820 stores, in addition to changing signs,taking inventory and cleaning up.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prices farmers got for raw products declined0.7 percent from January to February but still averaged 14 percentmore than a year ago, Agriculture Department figures show.   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in itspreliminary report released Tuesday that lower prices for soybeans,lettuce, milk and corn were mostly responsible for the decline fromthe January average.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the Federal CommunicationsCommission said he will press toward overhaul of ATandamp;T's pricingsystem despite lawmaker concern the plan will lead to windfallprofits at the expense of consumers.   After testimony before skeptical members of the Housetelecommunications and finance subcommittee, FCC chairman DennisPatrick said Tuesday the agency will vote on the ``rate cap'' planfor interstate services on March 16. The plan would take effect July1 if approved unless blocked by Congress.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Stock prices rose slightly Tuesday in what analysts called areflex response to recent declines. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials rose 8.03 points to 2,258.39. Elsewhere, bonds finishedhigher, the dollar finished mixed and oil prices declined.</TEXT></DOC>